’It Is OK For Me To Have Everything I Want’
Anthony Burrill 2005
Letterpress poster

Burrill’s early work played with found and instructional texts mixed with the language of self-help guides. The text for ’It Is OK For Me To Have Everything I Want’ comes from a familiar self-help mantra designed to assuage consumerist guilt which Burrill found in a newspaper article. His intention was to question that idea, but once the poster was released many took the message at face value, assuming that he was endorsing it. This confusion, which Burrill puts down to his own ‘wooly thinking’, was an early lesson in the pitfalls of working with such messages. Once Burrill had seen how the work was being received, he withdrew it from sale. It is not OK for you to have everything you want after all.

Currently exhibited as part of ‘Flop Art’, curated by @kesselskramerlondon at the Vans store, Covent Garden. All proceeds donated to @sheltercharity
